1783563847601817	mess-dev	itc:v3:AWKTOcmSTM5M8lAAAAAAQa3darbreoAAAAExAQ		item.create	bn-38nz	{"description":"# Context\n\nField report from mess (`~/src/mess`), written by the lead agent (mess-dev) after one intensive\nsession: 7 orchestrated waves, ~15 worker workspaces created by parallel subagents, 14\n`ws merge --into default --destroy` merges, several `ws sync` rebases, and one structured-conflict\nresolution. Root layout, maw v2. Overall verdict up front: the core loop (create → work →\ncheck → merge → destroy) is excellent for multi-agent work — isolation held, sibling\nauto-rebase during merges saved manual coordination repeatedly, and `--check` caught real\nproblems before they landed. The items below are the friction, worst first, each with a\nconcrete suggestion.\n\n# 1. Merge can silently clobber uncommitted trunk changes to tracked files (data loss)\n\n**What happened:** mess tracks its bones event journal (`.bones/events/2026-07.events`) in git.\nAll session bone-state transitions lived as an *uncommitted modification* of that tracked file\nat trunk. During a merge wave (`ws sync bn-gke` + structured-conflict resolve + `ws merge\n--destroy`), the trunk working-tree copy was restored to its committed content. An entire\nsession of bone history (19 done-transitions, comments) vanished silently — no warning, no\nbackup. No workspace branch had ever touched that file. We recovered only because the lead\nknew the full transition sequence and replayed it.\n\n**Why it stings:** maw's own safety promise is \"No work is ever lost in maw\" — and that holds\nbeautifully for *workspaces* (recovery snapshots on destroy). Trunk has no equivalent shield,\nyet merges perform checkout-like operations on the trunk working tree.\n\n**Suggestions (any one of these would have prevented it):**\n- Before any operation that rewrites trunk working-tree files, detect uncommitted modifications\n  to tracked files in the paths being written and **refuse** (like `git checkout` does), with a\n  `--force` escape hatch.\n- Or extend the recovery-snapshot machinery to trunk: snapshot the trunk working tree before\n  every merge, and surface it in `ws recover`.\n- Or auto-stash trunk dirt before the merge and pop after, reporting what was stashed.\n- Cheapest partial: print a loud warning listing dirty tracked files at merge time.\n\n# 2. `ws sync` commits conflict markers into workspace HEAD\n\n**What happened:** `ws sync bn-gke` hit a content conflict in `lib.rs` and *committed* the\nconflicted file — markers and all — into the workspace HEAD, apparently succeeding. The failure\nonly surfaced later, at `ws merge --check`, as \"unresolved conflict markers committed into HEAD\n(probably from a prior `maw ws sync`)\". If the merge check didn't grep for markers, broken code\nwould have landed on trunk.\n\n**Suggestion:** make sync behave like `git rebase`: stop with the working tree in a conflicted,\n*uncommitted* state, exit nonzero, and print the resolve/continue steps right there. Committing\na known-conflicted tree should never look like success. (The marker-grep in merge --check is a\ngood backstop — keep it — but it should be the second line of defense, not the first.)\n\n# 3. Structured-conflict presentation mutates the file itself\n\n**What happened:** the conflicted file's working copy began with a prepended header:\n\n    # structured conflict at crates/mess-log/src/lib.rs\n    # base blob: f1f6532...\n    # side epoch blob: 9d4aec8...\n\nThat header is *inside a Rust source file*. `#` is not a Rust comment; anyone (human or agent)\nwho resolves the markers but misses the header commits a syntax error. It also means the file\non disk is not any of the three sides, which confuses tooling and diffing.\n\n**Suggestions:**\n- Keep the file itself as plain git-style conflict markers only; put the blob metadata in a\n  sidecar (`.maw/conflicts/<ws>/<path>.meta`) or in `ws resolve --list` output (which already\n  exists and is good).\n- `ws resolve --keep both` concatenates sides; for the extremely common \"two workers each added\n  a line to the same list\" case (module declarations, dep lists, doc bullets), a smarter\n  union-merge option (`--keep union`, dedup + stable order) would resolve most real conflicts\n  we hit without hand-editing.\n\n# 4. Auto-rebase during sibling merges is great — but advertise the semantic risk\n\n**What happened:** merging bn-b2r auto-rebased sibling bn-3ps (\"2 commit(s) replayed\" — clean).\nTextually clean, semantically broken: bn-3ps's tests used an API that bn-b2r had just reworked,\nso the workspace no longer compiled. Nothing in the output suggested re-validating.\n\n**Suggestion:** after auto-rebasing a sibling over commits that touch files/crates the sibling\nalso touches (`ws overlap` already computes this), append a hint: \"rebased over N commits\ntouching M files your workspace also touches — re-run your test suite before merging.\" Even\nbetter: an optional per-workspace `postsync` hook (e.g. `cargo test -p <crate>`) that runs after\nsync/auto-rebase and reports pass/fail in `ws list`.\n\n# 5. Epoch drift from legitimate trunk commits is noisy and manual\n\n**What happened:** the lead legitimately commits directly to trunk in root layout (config fixes,\ndocs one-liners, the journal commit above). Every such commit makes every subsequent\n`ws merge --check` print \"trunk has 1 commit not made through maw; the epoch is behind\" until a\nmanual `maw epoch sync`. It's harmless but trains users to ignore warnings, and the remedy is\nalways the same command.\n\n**Suggestion:** when trunk is strictly ahead by committed work (fast-forward case, no divergence),\nauto-sync the epoch during merge/check (or offer `epoch.autosync = true` in config). Reserve the\nwarning for actual divergence.\n\n# 6. Destroy + cwd interaction\n\n**What happened:** ran `maw ws merge <ws> --into default --destroy` from a shell whose cwd was\ninside that workspace. The merge succeeded; every subsequent command in the chain failed with\nconfusing errors because the directory under the shell had been deleted.\n\n**Suggestion:** maw can't fix the parent shell's cwd, but it can detect `$PWD` (or `cwd`) inside\nthe workspace being destroyed and print one line: \"note: your current directory was destroyed;\ncd back to the project root.\" Cheap, saves real confusion — especially for agents chaining\ncommands with `&&`.\n\n# 7. Small output/UX nits\n\n- Merge success output ends with the push suggestion; there's no single grep-able line like\n  `[OK] merged <ws> into default @ <short-sha>`. Agents parse output with `tail`/`grep`; one\n  stable summary line per operation (like `--check`'s `[OK] Ready to merge`) would help a lot.\n  A `--format json` on `ws merge`/`ws sync`/`ws list` would help even more (bn has this; maw\n  mostly doesn't).\n- `ws list` lifecycle labels (`active (+N to merge)`, `committed-unintegrated`, `ready to merge`)\n  are genuinely useful — consider documenting the full label vocabulary in `ws list --help`.\n- `ws sync` on an already-current workspace prints \"up to date\" — good. `ws sync` right after a\n  sibling merge already auto-rebased it also prints \"up to date\" — also good, just noting the\n  auto-rebase NOTE only appears in the *merge* output of the other workspace, where the owner of\n  this workspace may never see it.\n\n# What worked well (keep it)\n\n- Isolation model: ~15 concurrent agent workspaces, zero cross-contamination.\n- `--check` before `--destroy` as a ritual: caught the stale-workspace and marker cases.\n- Auto-rebase of siblings on merge: removed nearly all manual rebase choreography.\n- `maw exec <ws> -- ...`: exactly right for orchestrators driving many workspaces.\n- Recovery snapshots on destroy: never needed them, but they changed how confidently we could\n  `--destroy` on every merge.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Item 1 addressed (trunk uncommitted-tracked-file protection in some form) — this is the\n      only data-loss-class item\n- [ ] Item 2 addressed (sync stops on conflict instead of committing markers)\n- [ ] Remaining items triaged into follow-up bones or explicitly declined with rationale","kind":"task","labels":["feedback"],"title":"Field report: multi-agent orchestration friction in mess (merge clobbers trunk dirt, sync commits conflict markers, more)"}	blake3:XqButdRgPtzDDdJ024CNWiRhANyHu_yJVVMot1ji1XQ
1783564902290921	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyohQ		item.create	bn-1xmk	{"description":"From bn-38nz item 1 (mess field report: uncommitted .bones/events/2026-07.events at trunk silently restored to committed content during a merge wave; no workspace touched the file).\n\nINVESTIGATION FINDINGS (verified on current HEAD):\nTrunk is NOT unprotected by design — update_default_workspace (merge.rs:5322) wraps the trunk checkout in snapshot_working_copy (stash-create, merge.rs:5454) -> checkout_to (merge.rs:5468 -> checkout_impl.rs:97, overwrite_existing=true, no tracked-dirty check) -> replay_snapshot_with_merge_protection (merge.rs:5489-5511). But this cycle is best-effort RECOVERY, not a guard, with three silent failure modes:\n\n(a) snapshot_working_copy (working_copy.rs:446) returns Ok(None) when status reports clean at that instant (net staged/unstaged cancellation, or content == anchor_epoch) — same Ok(None) ambiguity bn-3mpx fixed for capture_before_destroy. Then checkout overwrites with no snapshot, no warning.\n\n(b) THE EVENTS-JOURNAL CASE: replay_snapshot_with_merge_protection honors .gitattributes merge drivers (bn-17o5, working_copy.rs:853-870) ONLY for files in stash_paths INTERSECT resolved_paths. A dirty trunk file no workspace touched is restored by bare repo.stash_apply (working_copy.rs:784) — union semantics bypassed; if stash base (anchor_epoch) differs from post-checkout tree the file can silently resolve to the committed side.\n\n(c) On SnapshotReplayResult::Clean the ephemeral ref refs/manifold/snapshot/<ws> is DELETED (merge.rs:5516, working_copy.rs:1133). A wrongly-Clean replay leaves no recoverable backup. The snapshot ref is also invisible to ws recover.\n\nAlso: no pre-merge dirty-trunk visibility — assert_sources_clean_for_merge (merge.rs:2804) inspects only sources; the only trunk-dirt look is the FF-absorb disjointness predicate (merge.rs:3048), non-FF merges never check.\n\nDESIGN DECISION (lead): do NOT refuse on dirty trunk — the lead workflow legitimately keeps dirty tracked files (bones journal) across many merges; refusal trains --force habits. Instead make preserve-and-replay actually safe:\n\n1. DURABLE SNAPSHOT: before checkout_to in update_default_workspace, pin a durable recovery ref (refs/manifold/recovery/default/<ts>, reuse capture_before_destroy machinery from capture.rs:101) surfaced by maw ws recover. Keep it even on clean replay (subject to normal gc policy). The ephemeral snapshot ref can remain for replay mechanics.\n2. FIX MODE (b): non-overlapping stash files must also honor merge drivers / proper 3-way semantics on replay — or at minimum verify replay fidelity: after replay, compare each dirty path's final content against expected; on mismatch print a LOUD warning naming the recovery ref and exact maw ws recover command.\n3. FIX MODE (a): distinguish \"genuinely clean\" from stash_create None (mirror bn-3mpx).\n4. VISIBILITY: at merge start, when trunk has uncommitted tracked modifications, print one line listing them: \"preserving N uncommitted trunk file(s) across merge (recovery ref pinned)\". merge --check should mention dirty trunk files too.\n\nTESTS REQUIRED (coverage gap is why this class survived): uncommitted tracked file at trunk untouched by any workspace survives merge byte-for-byte; the merge=union journal case (append-only file, epoch advanced); snapshot-None case; recovery ref visible in ws recover; fidelity-mismatch path prints recovery instructions.\n\nRelated bones: bn-17o5, bn-3mpx, bn-34dg/bn-25wy (sync got refusals; merge->trunk never did), bn-1r81, bn-3r8s.","kind":"bug","labels":["bn-38nz-followup"],"size":"l","title":"Merge silently clobbers uncommitted tracked trunk files: make trunk preserve-and-replay uphold the Prime Invariant","urgency":"urgent"}	blake3:17lfXcT9LP-sUyTq0-uf5djNKZNxmYCapnQqKqYDaRU
