1783614799992890	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEywxQ		item.create	bn-1nmh	{"description":"cargo build/test/clippy with --features bench fails: non-exhaustive match on &Op in maw-bench (crates/maw-bench, around a match ending ~line 148) missing Op::Advance arm. Pre-existing, found while fixing bn-zox8 — no CI job compiles the bench feature, so it rotted when Advance was added. Fix the match; consider adding a bench-feature clippy/build lane to just check or the faithful-clippy recipe so feature-gated crates can't rot silently.","kind":"bug","size":"s","title":"bench feature build broken: maw-bench doesn't handle Op::Advance (E0004)"}	blake3:5ET4uo1bO0j9_De_PBou1dFc-bKJQGwUzjdyD2rSoyY
1783619611486044	mess-dev	itc:v3:AWKTOcmSTM5M8lAAAAAAQa3darbreoAAAAExAw		item.create	bn-rah2	{"description":"# Context\n\nFollow-up field report from mess (~/src/mess, root layout), same orchestration setup as\nbn-38nz. Observed on **maw 1.0.0-pre.10** — i.e. WITH the bn-38nz fixes installed — during\na wave of 4 merges on 2026-07-09. This looks like a possible regression from the new\nuncommitted-work-preservation machinery: the preservation now happens, but for *sibling\nworkspaces* it preserves the working tree while silently resetting the branch pointer.\n\n# What happened\n\nFour worker workspaces existed, each with exactly one committed work commit on top of the\nsame base commit 449c85f (\"chore: bones journal\"):\n\n- bn-1d0 → 9966703 (this one got merged first)\n- bn-3da → b8b45be\n- bn-221 → f61a8e3\n- bn-1bn → a5d88b2\n\nAll four verified clean immediately before merging: `git -C <ws> status --short` clean,\nwork commit at HEAD.\n\nThen: `maw ws merge bn-1d0 --into default --destroy --message \"...\"` — succeeded normally.\n\nImmediately after, ALL THREE sibling workspaces were in this state:\n\n- **HEAD reset back to the base commit 449c85f** — the work commit no longer at HEAD\n  (still present in the object store as a dangling commit; `git cat-file -t b8b45be` → commit).\n- **The work content still present in the working tree as uncommitted changes**\n  (`git diff <old-commit> -- crates/` empty, i.e. tree byte-identical to the lost commit).\n- Files that the lost commit had *added* (e.g. bn-1bn's new `crates/mess-index/src/columnar/`\n  directory) were back to **untracked** status.\n- In bn-3da a fresh stash appeared: `stash@{0}: WIP on main: 449c85f chore: bones journal —\n  wave 13 comments` — which smells like an auto-stash/preserve path that restored the files\n  but never restored (or re-wrote) the branch ref. (Note stashes are repo-global across\n  worktrees, so this stash showed up in every workspace's `git stash list`.)\n\nNo warning or NOTE in the merge output mentioned the siblings at all — no auto-rebase lines,\nno \"preserving uncommitted files\" lines for them. The merge output looked identical to a\nmerge with no siblings.\n\n# Why it stings\n\n- `maw ws sync <sibling>` then refuses: \"has uncommitted changes that would be lost by\n  sync. Commit or stash first.\" So the very next protocol step after a merge (sync the next\n  workspace) hard-fails, and the suggested remedy (commit) requires the operator to\n  understand that the tree is the lost commit's content. An agent that instead ran\n  `git checkout -- .` or `maw ws undo` at that point would have **destroyed reviewed,\n  approved work** — the state actively invites exactly that mistake, because \"uncommitted\n  changes I don't recognize\" usually means junk.\n- The reported provenance chain breaks: reviewers approved commit X at HEAD; by merge time\n  HEAD is the base commit. In an adversarial-review protocol (ours), that's\n  indistinguishable from a worker faking a commit — we only recovered confidently because\n  `git diff <lost-commit>` proved byte-identity.\n- It is silent. Nothing in the merge output says the sibling refs were touched.\n\n# Recovery that worked (for the record)\n\nFor each sibling: verify `git diff <lost-commit> -- crates/` is empty → `git add` +\n`git commit` (same message) → `maw ws sync` → re-run tests → merge. No content was lost.\n\n# Suggestions\n\n- If the new preservation machinery (auto-stash / snapshot-and-restore) runs over sibling\n  workspaces during a merge, it must **restore the branch ref too**, not just the working\n  tree. Preserve-then-reapply should be ref-faithful: a workspace whose HEAD was at commit X\n  before the merge should have HEAD at X (or a rebased X') after.\n- If the ref reset is intentional (e.g. pre-rebase state parking), make it loud and\n  self-healing: a NOTE per affected sibling in the merge output, and make the next\n  `ws sync` recognize the parked state and finish the job (re-commit/replay automatically)\n  instead of refusing with \"commit or stash first\".\n- Add a post-merge invariant check to maw's own test suite: for every sibling workspace,\n  (HEAD-before ∈ {HEAD-after, ancestor-of-HEAD-after-via-rebase}) and working tree clean if\n  it was clean before.\n- Repro sketch: root layout; ws A and B each one commit ahead of the same epoch; commit at\n  trunk directly (epoch behind by 2 — our state had 2 out-of-maw journal commits, which may\n  matter since the merge printed \"trunk has 2 commits not made through maw; the merge will\n  absorb them\"); merge A with --destroy; inspect B's HEAD.\n\n# One more small one\n\n`maw ws sync` refuses on a workspace whose only dirt is untracked scratch dirs, and the\nrefusal persists even after the paths are ignored via `.git/info/exclude` (git status\n--short clean, maw still says \"uncommitted changes\"). So maw's dirty-check doesn't honor\ngit's exclude mechanisms (jj-style snapshotting?). Suggest: honor gitignore/exclude the way\ngit does, or name the offending paths in the error so the operator knows what to remove.\n\n# Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] Root cause of the sibling HEAD reset identified (suspect: bn-38nz preservation\n      machinery interacting with sibling workspaces / epoch-behind absorption)\n- [ ] Sibling workspaces survive an adjacent merge ref-faithfully (or the parked state is\n      loud + self-healing via sync)\n- [ ] Regression test covering the repro sketch above\n- [ ] Dirty-check vs info/exclude behavior clarified or fixed","kind":"bug","labels":["feedback","data-loss"],"size":"m","title":"Merge silently resets sibling workspaces' branch pointers to base (work left uncommitted in tree)"}	blake3:VU75378zVX9AcDQPcduUUwsasrJpB4-49331VRr3YZM
1783619636707786	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEyxBQ		item.create	bn-3b0k	{"description":"bn-rah2: ws merge --destroy silently resets sibling workspaces' branch pointers, dangling commits, inviting data loss on next ws sync — possible regression from bn-38nz preservation machinery","kind":"task","title":"bn-rah2: ws merge --destroy silently resets sibling workspaces' branch pointers, dangling commits, inviting data loss on next ws sync — possible regression from bn-38nz preservation machinery"}	blake3:Uk6yMEDjf919h0NQ7SLsr0INnLlne0ksV8aO0QP8yoM
