1783647303533097	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy1xQ		item.create	bn-2rnq	{"description":"GOAL: turn the Prime Invariant from a design goal into a runtime-enforced contract. After every epoch mutation, maw itself verifies no sibling workspace lost committed work — and proves it in the output.\n\nMOTIVATION (evidence): bn-rah2 (2026-07) — FF-absorb raw-wrote sibling worktree HEADs, orphaning committed-ahead siblings. It shipped in a tagged release and was caught by a FIELD REPORT from another agent team, not by maw. An inline post-mutation auditor would have caught it at runtime on first occurrence, refused, and pinned recovery refs. Same story for the bn-38nz trunk dirty-file clobber (bn-1xmk): silent loss, detected by the victim.\n\nDESIGN:\n1. Pre-mutation capture: at the start of every epoch-mutating operation (ws merge incl. FF-absorb/auto-rebase, ws sync --rebase, ws advance, epoch sync), snapshot each sibling workspace's current HEAD OID (cheap: read refs, no tree work).\n2. Post-mutation audit: after the mutation completes but BEFORE declaring success, for each sibling verify its pre-op HEAD commit is still reachable from (new workspace HEAD) ∪ (new epoch) ∪ (any recovery ref pinned during the op). Use gix graph traversal; cap cost with a merge-base/ahead-behind check rather than full walks.\n3. On success: print one proof line, e.g. `INVARIANT: verified 3 sibling workspace(s) — no committed work orphaned`. Keep it to one line (agents are token-conscious) and add structured fields to --format json outputs (`invariant: {siblings_checked, orphaned: []}`).\n4. On violation: (a) pin a recovery ref at every orphaned HEAD immediately (refs/manifold/recovery/<ws>/invariant-<ts>), (b) print a loud INVARIANT VIOLATION block naming the workspace, the orphaned OID, and the exact `maw ws recover --ref ...` command, (c) exit nonzero. Do NOT attempt automatic rollback of the epoch in v1 — pin + report is the safe primitive (rollback can come later via the oplog). The dirty working-tree side is already covered by bn-1xmk's fidelity verify; this bone is about COMMITTED work (refs/commits).\n5. Config: `invariant.audit = true` default on. Escape hatch `invariant.audit = false` for perf-sensitive giant repos, but the audit must be cheap enough that nobody needs it.\n6. Record the audit result in the oplog entry for the mutation (extend the payload or add a note field) so `ws history` shows which epoch advances were verified.\n\nSCOPE GUARD: this is an AUDITOR, not new mutation logic. It must not change what merges do — only observe, pin, and report. Read-only against worktrees.\n\nTESTS: (a) normal merge with committed-ahead sibling → proof line, siblings_checked correct; (b) simulated violation (test hook or #[cfg(test)] fault that skips the rah2 replay) → violation block, recovery ref pinned, nonzero exit, orphaned commit recoverable; (c) FF-absorb path covered (the bn-rah2 repro from tests/merge_ff_absorb.rs extended with the auditor assertions); (d) audit disabled via config → no proof line, no behavior change; (e) JSON field shape.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- Every epoch-mutating command prints the one-line proof (or violation block) — merge, sync --rebase, advance, epoch sync.\n- A deliberately induced bn-rah2-style regression is caught: nonzero exit + pinned recovery ref + copy-pasteable recover command.\n- Overhead <100ms for 10 siblings on a warm repo (measure; it's ref reads + merge-bases).\n- just check green; no change to any existing merge semantics.\n","kind":"task","labels":["reliability","v1-0"],"size":"l","title":"Prime-Invariant runtime auditor: post-mutation sibling reachability proof on every epoch mutation"}	blake3:j9HfeBUTRopwLBHB1daUfPn-fj6NPJ1mLaPSENcVOuM
1783647303780898	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2BQ		item.create	bn-13rc	{"description":"GOAL: a repo-level single-writer lock so two maw processes can never interleave epoch mutations. Multi-agent orchestration is maw's core use case; today only `sync --rebase` (per-workspace, bn-1d1g) and create take locks — `ws merge` (incl. FF-absorb + auto-rebase of siblings), `ws advance`, `epoch sync`, and `gc` take none.\n\nMOTIVATION (evidence): 2026-07-08, this repo — an auto-spawned dev loop (maw-dev/0 edict responder) ran `ws merge --destroy` concurrently with the lead's review/merge session. It happened to win cleanly, but two concurrent merges interleaving PREPARE/BUILD/COMMIT phases on the same epoch would race write_epoch_current, branch update, and sibling auto-rebase with undefined results. The bn-1d1g lock exists precisely because this class already bit once at workspace scope.\n\nDESIGN:\n1. Reuse the proven mechanism from crates/maw-cli/src/workspace/sync/lock.rs: fs4 advisory flock on a lockfile, crash-safe (OS releases on process death), lockfile never deleted. New scope: `<repo>/.manifold/locks/epoch.lock` — ONE lock for the whole repo's epoch state.\n2. Take the lock (exclusive) around the mutating section of: ws merge (all of PREPARE→COMMIT→auto-rebase→cleanup), ws sync --rebase (in ADDITION to its per-ws lock — take epoch lock first, always same order to avoid deadlock), ws advance, epoch sync, gc (ref sweeps + record prunes), ws destroy (recovery pinning + record write). Read-only commands (list/status/diff/history/recover listing) must NOT take it.\n3. Contention behavior: default is to wait briefly (e.g. try_lock, then poll up to ~10s with progress note \"waiting for epoch lock held by <info>\"), then fail with a self-contained message: what's holding it (see 4), and \"To fix: wait for it to finish, or if the process is dead the lock auto-released — re-run\".\n4. Holder metadata: on acquire, write `{pid, command line, agent (from $AGENT if set), started_at}` INTO the lockfile (the flock is on the fd, so writing content is safe). On contention, read and print it. Stale content with no flock holder = harmless (previous crash) — never treat content alone as \"locked\".\n5. `--no-wait` flag or config for orchestrators that prefer immediate failure; exit code distinct from other errors so scripts can retry.\n6. Doctor check: `epoch-lock` — report if the lockfile is currently flocked (informational; shows holder metadata).\n\nDEADLOCK/ORDERING RULE (must be documented in the lock module): epoch lock is always acquired BEFORE any per-workspace lock, never after. Audit existing per-ws lock call sites for compliance.\n\nTESTS: (a) two concurrent merges — second one waits then succeeds after first completes (spawn real subprocesses); (b) holder metadata printed on contention; (c) crash-safety — kill -9 a holder mid-merge, next acquire succeeds immediately; (d) read commands don't block while a merge runs; (e) sync's existing per-ws lock still works, ordering respected; (f) --no-wait exits distinctly.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- Two maw processes mutating the same repo serialize; the loser gets a clear who-holds-it message, never a corrupted/interleaved state.\n- kill -9 leaves no stuck lock.\n- No measurable overhead on the uncontended path.\n- just check green.\n","kind":"task","labels":["reliability"],"size":"m","title":"Repo-level single-writer epoch lock: serialize concurrent maw mutations"}	blake3:t7w9XvABMIPNUkGpLBEPw6KGLrBgcVeqAVNGjybVd_s
1783647304014453	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2RQ		item.create	bn-117s	{"description":"GOAL: `maw undo` — one top-level command that reverses the last epoch mutation (merge / absorb / sync-advance / epoch sync). The single most confidence-instilling property a VCS-adjacent tool can have (jj's oplog undo): every operation becomes reversible, every bug becomes an inconvenience instead of a data-loss scare.\n\nEXISTING PLUMBING (build on it, don't reinvent): crates/maw-core/src/oplog/ already has per-workspace op logs with rich payloads — Merge {sources, epoch_before, epoch_after}, Create, Destroy, Snapshot {patch_set_oid}, Compensate {target_op, reason}, RebaseReplay — plus global_view.rs and checkpoint.rs. `maw ws undo <name>` already exists for LOCAL workspace changes via Compensate. What's missing is the repo-level command that walks the global view and compensates an EPOCH transition.\n\nDESIGN:\n1. `maw undo` (no args): identify the most recent epoch-mutating operation from the global oplog view; print what it was (op kind, sources, epoch_before → epoch_after, timestamp) and undo it. `maw undo --dry-run` prints the plan without acting. `maw undo <op-id>` targets a specific op (id as shown in `maw ops log`, see 4).\n2. Undo of a merge: move epoch + branch back to epoch_before (via the guarded native HEAD/ref movers — NEVER raw ref writes; the bn-8flz/bn-29z8 invariant), restore destroyed source workspaces from their recovery snapshots/destroy records (they were pinned at destroy time), and replay/restore sibling workspaces to their pre-merge state where the auto-rebase moved them (their pre-op HEADs are in the oplog / reflog). The merge commit itself stays reachable via a pinned ref (refs/manifold/recovery/undo/<ts>) so undo is itself undoable (`maw undo` after `maw undo` = redo).\n3. SAFETY RAILS: refuse (with exact reasons + To fix) when: the branch was pushed since the op (compare with origin — warn + require --force since remote history diverges); trunk has new commits on top of epoch_after (out-of-maw work would be orphaned — offer the recovery path); a workspace involved was since re-created/modified. Dirty trunk files: preserve via the bn-1xmk preserve-and-replay machinery, same as merge does.\n4. `maw ops log` (or extend existing surface if one exists): repo-level view of recent operations across workspaces (global_view), one line each with id, kind, epochs, sources, timestamp — this is what makes undo targetable and auditable. --format json included.\n5. Record the undo itself as a Compensate op in the oplog with the target op id — durable audit trail, visible in ws history / ops log.\n6. Out of scope for this bone: undoing gc (records deleted are gone — document), undoing recover, multi-step undo stacks beyond undo-of-undo.\n\nTESTS: (a) merge → undo → workspaces restored with their commits, epoch/branch back at epoch_before, merge commit still pinned; (b) undo → undo = redo; (c) refusal when trunk advanced post-merge (out-of-maw commit) with clear message; (d) refusal/--force when pushed; (e) dirty trunk file survives undo byte-for-byte; (f) ops log shows the mutation and the compensation; (g) sibling that was auto-rebased by the merge returns to its pre-merge HEAD; (h) works from any cwd via maw exec.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- `maw ws merge X --destroy` followed by `maw undo` leaves the repo indistinguishable from before the merge (workspace X back with its commits, epoch/branch/siblings restored), with the merge result still recoverable.\n- Every refusal message says exactly why and what to do.\n- All ref movement through the guarded native movers; zero raw fs writes to refs/HEAD.\n- just check green.\n","kind":"task","labels":["ux","reliability"],"size":"l","title":"maw undo: repo-level oplog-powered undo of the last epoch mutation (+ maw ops log)"}	blake3:MX4hdOD4DtFuJnRFpK2TYmZPQn_E-iv5c-PbK09-QCI
1783647304243119	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2hQ		item.create	bn-2bcx	{"description":"GOAL: extend DST (deterministic simulation testing) coverage to the specific op paths that produced 2026-07's escaped bugs — the gaps that remain AFTER bn-2byw widened the soak to Advance + real merge/sync + concurrency.\n\nMOTIVATION (evidence): every recent escape lived exactly where DST doesn't look:\n- bn-rah2: FF-absorb (reconcile_epoch_with_branch) orphaned committed-ahead siblings when absorbing out-of-maw trunk commits — shipped in a release, caught by a field report.\n- bn-1xmk (bn-38nz item 1): trunk preserve-and-replay clobbered uncommitted tracked trunk files whose committed content changed (merge=union journal case) — caught by a field report.\n- bn-3uou: gc --refs desynced recovery refs from destroy records — caught by a user clearing doctor warns.\nThe soak (bn-2byw) exercises merge/sync/advance concurrency but, per these escapes, does not model: out-of-maw trunk commits (the trigger for FF-absorb), dirty uncommitted trunk files riding through merges, or the gc/destroy-record/recover lifecycle.\n\nSCOPE — add to the DST harness (maw-scenario Op surface + maw-assurance oracles + the sim driver):\n1. New op: OutOfMawCommit — a commit made directly on trunk outside maw (this is what arms FF-absorb/reconcile). Parameters: touching paths disjoint vs overlapping with workspace-touched paths.\n2. New op/state: DirtyTrunkWrite — uncommitted modification to a tracked file in the default workspace (optionally one whose committed content will change via a pending merge — the bn-1xmk killer case; include a merge=union .gitattributes variant if feasible).\n3. New ops: Gc {recovery_snapshots, older_than}, Recover {workspace} — model the destroy→record→ref→gc→recover lifecycle.\n4. New oracles (the point of the exercise):\n   - SiblingRefFaithfulness: after any op, every workspace's previously-committed HEAD remains reachable from its current HEAD ∪ epoch ∪ recovery refs (the bn-rah2 class).\n   - TrunkDirtyPreservation: uncommitted trunk bytes survive any op or are explicitly surfaced in a recovery ref (the bn-1xmk class).\n   - RecordRefCoherence: no destroy record claims a recovery ref that does not exist (the bn-3uou class); every gc leaves records↔refs coherent.\n5. Wire the new ops into both the fast DST tier (just check's dst-fast) at low intensity and the SG1 soak scenario mix. Respect determinism constraints (no wall-clock/randomness outside the seeded RNG).\n6. Regression seeds: encode the exact bn-rah2 and bn-1xmk incident shapes as named deterministic scenarios (like existing regression scenarios) so they run forever.\n\nIMPORTANT CONSTRAINTS:\n- Follow existing scenario/oracle idioms in maw-scenario and maw-assurance — read several existing ops/oracles first; match their style exactly.\n- maw-bench has a match on Op (crates/maw-bench/src/prompt.rs — recently fixed for Op::Advance, bn-1nmh): ADD ARMS for any new Op variants, and check ALL non-exhaustive matches on Op across the workspace compile under --features bench AND --features assurance (just sg2-bench-clippy must stay green — it exists to catch exactly this).\n- Keep dst-fast runtime budget: new ops at low weight; the heavy mix belongs in the soak profile.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- Reverting the bn-rah2 fix (locally, as an experiment — do not commit the revert) makes the SiblingRefFaithfulness oracle fail within a small bounded number of steps on the regression seed. Same experiment documented for bn-1xmk / TrunkDirtyPreservation if practical.\n- New ops appear in soak scenario mix; dst-fast still fits its time budget; just check + sg2-bench-clippy green.\n- A short note in the bone comments: which op/oracle would have caught each of the three 2026-07 escapes.\n","kind":"task","labels":["dst","assurance"],"size":"l","title":"DST coverage for the 2026-07 escape paths: FF-absorb, dirty-trunk replay, gc/recover lifecycle + oracles"}	blake3:sMWcZ1erOe1fp9ssVBFNRiCSQCmZLzreqQ8-mqCeom0
1783647304477183	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy2xQ		item.create	bn-1uot	{"description":"GOAL: `maw fsck` — an offline deep verifier of ALL manifold state with a versioned invariant catalog, safe `--repair`, and CI-friendly exit codes. Doctor accretes checks reactively (bn-3uou being the latest); fsck inverts that: enumerate every cross-artifact invariant once, check them all, repair what is provably safe.\n\nRELATIONSHIP TO DOCTOR: doctor = quick environment/health triage for interactive use (keep it). fsck = exhaustive state verification (slower is fine). Doctor's state-coherence checks (dangling-snapshots, abandoned-with-snapshot, destroy-record-unpinned, stale-head-refs, merge-state, ghost-working-copy) should be BACKED BY the same invariant catalog so the logic lives once — doctor calls a fast subset, fsck runs everything. Refactor those checks into the shared catalog rather than duplicating.\n\nINVARIANT CATALOG (each with stable id, severity, description, check fn, optional repair fn):\n- refs: every refs/manifold/* ref points at an existing object of the right kind; epoch/current parses and its commit exists; per-workspace epoch refs consistent with .manifold metadata.\n- workspaces: every registered workspace has a live worktree dir and vice versa (orphan worktree dirs / ghost registrations); each workspace HEAD is a valid commit; git worktree bookkeeping (.git/worktrees/*) agrees with maw's registry.\n- destroy records ↔ recovery refs: bn-3uou coherence (record claims ref → ref exists), latest.json points at an existing record, record OIDs resolve to objects.\n- oplog: entries parse, referenced OIDs (patch_set_oid etc.) exist, per-workspace logs' checkpoints valid.\n- merge-state: no stale in-flight merge journal without a live process (bn-2wyh class).\n- locks: lockfiles with holder metadata but no flock holder = stale-but-harmless (info only).\n- epoch/branch: configured branch exists and epoch/current is an ancestor-or-equal of it (or a documented allowed divergence).\n\nCLI:\n- `maw fsck` — run everything, grouped report, summary line `fsck: N invariants checked, M violations (K repairable)`. Exit 0 clean / nonzero on violations (distinct codes for warn-only vs corruption).\n- `maw fsck --repair` — apply only repairs that are provably safe and non-destructive (re-pin a ref to a still-existing OID from a record, delete a ghost registration for a nonexistent dir, remove stale merge-state with no live pid). NEVER deletes objects, records, or refs that pin content — destructive cleanup stays in `maw gc`. Print each repair as it happens. `--dry-run` composes.\n- `--format json`: array of {id, severity, status, detail, repair} — versioned shape (include a `fsck_schema: 1` field).\n- Each violation's text includes the exact fix command (AGENTS.md output rules).\n\nINTEGRATION: run `maw fsck` at the end of the consolidated-sim harness (notes/consolidated-sim.sh) and consider a cheap subset invocation from the SG1 soak status script — mention feasibility in the report, do not gold-plate.\n\nTESTS: for EACH catalog invariant, an integration test that (a) constructs the violating state by hand, (b) asserts fsck reports it with the right id/severity, (c) where a repair exists, asserts --repair fixes it and a second fsck is clean, and (d) asserts --repair on a healthy repo is a no-op (byte-level: no refs/records change). Plus: fsck on this real repo's shape (fresh TestRepo after various ops) is clean; exit codes; JSON schema shape test.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- `maw fsck` on a healthy repo: all green, exit 0. On every hand-constructed violation: correct detection + actionable message.\n- `--repair` fixes the safe subset and NEVER removes recoverable content (destructive = gc's job; fsck must say so when it declines).\n- doctor's coherence checks and fsck share one catalog implementation (no logic duplication).\n- just check green.\n","kind":"task","labels":["reliability"],"size":"l","title":"maw fsck: offline deep state verifier with versioned invariant catalog and safe --repair"}	blake3:zwqNCt5yNZrSMmpchB997JeO6SNe8sZabSbLtKK5XxM
1783647304707009	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3BQ		item.create	bn-1obp	{"description":"GOAL: automate the release mechanics so a release is one command + review, and publish breakage is caught in PR CI instead of on tag day.\n\nMOTIVATION (evidence): the crates.io publish chain was broken from pre.6 to pre.10 (missing maw-scenario in the chain; version skew across crates). Every release requires manually bumping ~19 internal path-dep `version = \"X\"` strings across Cargo.tomls in lockstep (global sed), regenerating Cargo.lock, writing CHANGELOG, tagging — each step has bitten at least once (pre.7 shipped with red tests; clippy drift broke a release commit's CI).\n\nSCOPE:\n1. `maw release prepare vX.Y.Z` (or a just recipe / xtask — pick what fits the repo's idioms; maw release currently only tags+pushes): does the lockstep version bump across all Cargo.tomls (workspace version + all internal path-dep version strings), regenerates Cargo.lock via cargo build/update -w, scaffolds a CHANGELOG.md section header with the version + date, and verifies README version references. Leaves the tree uncommitted for review. Idempotent; refuses if tree dirty (other than its own edits on re-run).\n2. PR CI publish dry-run: a workflow step (or extension of an existing workflow) that runs the same crate chain as publish.yml with `cargo publish --dry-run` on every PR touching Cargo.toml/Cargo.lock — so a broken publish chain or version skew fails BEFORE a tag exists. Keep it cheap (dry-run only, no network beyond index).\n3. A release-preflight check (`just release-preflight` or part of prepare): all versions consistent (workspace + internal deps + lock), CHANGELOG has a section for the target version, working tree clean, `just check` green marker (do not re-run the whole suite inside prepare — check freshness or instruct).\n4. Update AGENTS.md Release Instructions to the new flow.\n\nNON-GOALS: do not change publish.yml's actual publish chain semantics; do not auto-generate changelog content from commits (scaffold only); no auto-push/auto-tag from prepare.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- On a scratch branch: `release prepare v9.9.9-test` produces exactly the diff a manual release bump would (compare against the pre.10→pre.11 bump commit shape), and running it twice is a no-op the second time.\n- Intentionally skewing one internal version string makes both the preflight and the PR dry-run step fail with a message naming the file.\n- just check green; workflow YAML validated (actionlint if available, or careful review).\n","kind":"task","labels":["release"],"size":"m","title":"Release automation: lockstep version bump + publish dry-run in PR CI + preflight"}	blake3:7vzhaQtga1Flqu7QOqkx8XZshBiKPAC55zLwIV3v-_c
1783647304936181	maw-dev	itc:v3:AWKTmSTM_JOSSTQAAAAAQa7Vbfq6qsAAAAEy3RQ		item.create	bn-1n2b	{"description":"GOAL: make it impossible for a defined CI gate to silently not run — a meta-test that every Justfile gate recipe is wired into at least one GitHub workflow, plus fix the one known orphan.\n\nMOTIVATION (evidence): bn-1nmh (2026-07): the bench feature rotted for a full release cycle because no workflow compiled --features bench. While fixing it we found `sg1-assurance-clippy` has the same defect TODAY: defined in the Justfile, commented as \"a dedicated gate\", wired into NO workflow — the assurance/oracles feature stack can rot exactly like bench did.\n\nSCOPE:\n1. Wire `sg1-assurance-clippy` into .github/workflows/dst-faithful.yml as a step (same pattern as the sg2-bench-clippy step added in bn-1nmh, commit 790e01b9). Verify it currently passes; if it has accumulated lint debt (likely — it has never run in CI), fix that debt in the same workspace (see bn-1nmh's commit for the idiom: minimal #[allow] waivers matching existing repo style, real fixes where cheap).\n2. Add the meta-test: a test (tests/ci_lane_wiring.rs or similar) that parses the Justfile for gate recipes (naming convention: recipes matching `*-clippy`, `*-check`, or an explicit marker comment — pick a robust convention and document it in the Justfile header) and asserts each is referenced by at least one file under .github/workflows/. Parse textually (no just/yaml dependencies needed — grep-level matching is fine and robust). The test must FAIL if someone adds a `foo-clippy` recipe without wiring it, and must name the orphan recipe in the failure message.\n3. Opt-out mechanism for genuinely local-only recipes: a documented marker (e.g. `# ci: local-only` comment above the recipe) that the meta-test respects — so the convention doesn't block legitimate local tooling.\n4. Audit all existing Justfile recipes once and classify: wired / local-only-marked / orphan-to-fix. Report the classification in the bone comment.\n\nACCEPTANCE:\n- sg1-assurance-clippy runs green in dst-faithful.yml.\n- Deleting the sg2-bench-clippy step from the workflow (locally, as an experiment) makes the meta-test fail naming that recipe.\n- All current recipes classified; zero unexplained orphans.\n- just check green (the meta-test runs as part of it).\n","kind":"task","labels":["ci"],"size":"s","title":"CI lane-wiring meta-test + wire sg1-assurance-clippy into a workflow"}	blake3:S2DN1kBbxoza2BtJqmD3MI5uoCyozNQFiMK-FapOQfM
